From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Stephen O'Connor <stephen.r.oconnor92@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 5 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Cross-compile the ZeroMQ socket apps for the RV2 image

Upstream keeps the frame_* socket apps host-only (the block is guarded by
`NOT CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING`) on the assumption that a generic cross sysroot
need not carry libzmq. In the rv2-space-linux Yocto build the target sysroot
DOES provide libzmq (zeromq) and cppzmq via the recipe DEPENDS, so the apps
can and should cross-compile to be installed in the image.

Only the app/test targets in this block change behaviour; the guard's
underlying find_package(cppzmq)/find_library(zmq) logic is unchanged and now
resolves against the cross sysroot. The socket tests here are registered with
add_test (not gtest_discover_tests) under a cross toolchain, so nothing is
executed at build time.

Upstream-Status: Inappropriate [embedded/yocto-specific configuration]
Signed-off-by: Stephen O'Connor <stephen.r.oconnor92@gmail.com>
---
 CMakeLists.txt | 6 +++++-
 1 file changed, 5 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/CMakeLists.txt b/CMakeLists.txt
index 7537b0a..bdb39b5 100644
--- a/CMakeLists.txt
+++ b/CMakeLists.txt
@@ -665,7 +665,11 @@ add_test(NAME track_from_files COMMAND track_from_files)
 # ============================================================================
 # Socket apps link libzmq (a real runtime lib, not header-only), which a cross sysroot need
 # not carry — so keep them host-only even when the cross Boost headers are present.
-if(POLARIS_BUILD_ZMQ_APP AND NOT CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING)
+# rv2-space-linux (Yocto cross build): the target sysroot DOES carry libzmq (zeromq)
+# and cppzmq via the recipe DEPENDS, so the "a cross sysroot need not carry libzmq"
+# rationale for the host-only guard above does not hold here. Drop the
+# NOT CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING term so the frame_* socket apps cross-compile for the image.
+if(POLARIS_BUILD_ZMQ_APP)
   # cppzmq is header-only over libzmq. Prefer its CMake package; fall back to the
   # bare header + libzmq so it builds wherever cppzmq-devel/zeromq-devel are present.
   find_package(cppzmq QUIET)
